<script>
/* ===================== BLOG DATA ===================== */
var BLOG_POSTS = [
  {
    id: 'login-page-tutorial',
    title: 'Log in Page Tutorial',
    date: 'May 2025',
    category: 'Tableau Tutorial',
    readTime: '5 min read',
    excerpt: 'A step-by-step walkthrough of how to build a fully functional login page inside Tableau using parameters, calculated fields, and Dynamic Zone Visibility.',
    thumb: 'https://drive.google.com/thumbnail?id=1ZmLkNF4IOKUbXquwOyqi9HAuFQ8THHDt&sz=w1280',
    content: `
      <div class="post-cat-badge">Tableau Tutorial</div>
      <h1 class="post-title">Log in Page Tutorial</h1>
      <div class="post-meta-row">
        <span class="post-author">Tobiloba Babajide</span>
        <span class="post-sep"></span>
        <span class="post-date">May 2025</span>
        <span class="post-sep"></span>
        <span class="post-read-time">5 min read</span>
      </div>
      <div class="post-body">
        <p>Hi there, and welcome to my first-ever blog post on my website! In this quick tutorial, I'll walk you through how I built a login page for my latest business dashboard: the <a href="https://public.tableau.com/app/profile/tobiloba.babajide/viz/SampleSuperstoreDashboard_17470960865060/HomePage" target="_blank">Sample Superstore Dashboard</a>.</p>
        <p>It might look fancy at first glance, but trust me — creating a login page in Tableau is way easier than it seems. I'll break everything down step by step so you can build one yourself. Let's dive in!</p>

        <h3>Step 1 &ndash; Design the Login Page</h3>
        <p>The first step is to design the layout of the login page &mdash; where the logo, background, and login section will be. Technically, you could do this in Tableau, but it's much easier to design it using an external tool like <strong>Figma</strong>, PowerPoint, or Canva.</p>
        <p>For mine, I used Figma to build everything from scratch &mdash; the logo, the background, and the login section. Here's what the login page looks like initially:</p>
        <img class="post-img" src="https://drive.google.com/thumbnail?id=16ia_42i-Qc2U5NbYS6mLG-6iSBStPXMd&sz=w1280" alt="Login page design in Figma" />
        <p>You'll notice the login button is greyed out. That's on purpose! The button only becomes active when the user enters the correct password. Don't worry &mdash; I'll show you how to set this up too!</p>

        <h3>Step 2 &ndash; Create the Login Parameter</h3>
        <p>This is probably the most important part of the entire process. The login parameter allows users to type in a password and also controls whether the blue login button is shown or hidden (using <strong>Dynamic Zone Visibility</strong>).</p>
        <p>Here's how the parameter looks:</p>
        <img class="post-img" src="https://drive.google.com/thumbnail?id=1IQrr2FLbN3IQvpSWjxoQih-oIcybVuW_&sz=w1280" alt="Login Parameter setup in Tableau" />
        <p>Make sure to set a default value in the <strong>"Value when workbook opens"</strong> section &mdash; this is what users will see when they first open the dashboard. In my case, I used a calculated field called <strong>Log in default text</strong> to display: <em>"Type in your password."</em></p>

        <h3>Step 3 &ndash; Activate the Login Button</h3>
        <p>Next, you'll need a calculated field to control the visibility of the blue login button (which is just a navigation button that takes users to the main dashboard). Let's call it <strong>Hide Log in</strong>.</p>
        <p>The logic is super simple: check if the entered password matches the correct one, and return either TRUE or FALSE.</p>
        <div class="code-block">[Login Parameter] = "Tableau2025"</div>
        <p>If the user types in <strong>"Tableau2025"</strong>, it returns TRUE, which makes the login button visible. Otherwise, it returns FALSE.</p>

        <h3>Step 4 &ndash; Set Up Text and Hint</h3>
        <p>Now let's create some feedback for incorrect logins. When users enter anything other than "Tableau2025" or the default message, we want to display: <em>"Incorrect password! Try again"</em></p>
        <p>You can control this by setting up a calculated field called <strong>Log in text</strong>:</p>
        <div class="code-block">IF [Log in param] = 'Tableau2025' OR [Log in param] = 'Type in your password'
THEN ''
ELSE 'Incorrect password! Try again'
END</div>
        <p>Also, since this is just a demo, we can give users a little hint. I used a blank sheet with a tooltip to do this &mdash; you can get creative with how you display it!</p>

        <h3>Step 5 &ndash; Bringing It All Together</h3>
        <p>Now for the final part &mdash; putting everything into one clean, functional login page:</p>
        <img class="post-img" src="https://drive.google.com/thumbnail?id=1ZmLkNF4IOKUbXquwOyqi9HAuFQ8THHDt&sz=w1280" alt="Final login page in Tableau" />
        <p>For the navigation button, don't forget to use <strong>Dynamic Zone Visibility</strong> to control when the login button appears. Just check the box that says <em>"Control visibility using value"</em> and set the value to "Hide Login".</p>
        <p>Here's what that setup looks like:</p>
